## Q4: Texture-compositing + UV-island technique — confirmed approach

**Single CanvasTexture (2048×2048) is correct** over two separate textures/materials because:
- The body CylinderGeometry has one UV space; splitting it requires two mesh groups + two materials which complicates the wrap-all-around mode
- Single canvas compositor draws both islands in one pass; `texture.needsUpdate=true` on rAF throttle is efficient

**UV island pixel coordinates on a 2048×2048 canvas:**
- FRONT island: `x: 512→1536, y: 0→2048` (U 0.25→0.75 of body cylinder)
- BACK island: Since UVs wrap continuously and CylinderGeometry U goes 0→1, the back occupies U 0.75→1.0 AND U 0.0→0.25, which in canvas pixels = `x: 1536→2048` plus `x: 0→512` (two strips, left-edge + right-edge of canvas) — in wrap-all-around mode this is seamless
- For wrap-all-around mode: draw the single image at full 2048px width → it naturally occupies all U space, wrapping around the cylinder with the seam hidden at U=0 (right underarm)
- For front/back separate mode: draw frontImage into `[512,0,1024,2048]` and backImage into left+right strips

**<100ms recomposite:** a 2048×2048 CanvasContext drawImage call takes ~2-5ms. The bottleneck is texture upload to GPU; `texture.needsUpdate=true` is cheap. rAF throttle (requestAnimationFrame gate) prevents queuing multiple recomposes. Add a 16ms debounce on slider input before firing compositor.

**Keeping existing Decal (back text) working:** after switching to CylinderGeometry, the Decal must target the back face. Set Decal `position={[0, 0.2, -0.38]}` (rear of cylinder radius), `rotation={[0, Math.PI, 0]}`. The canvas compositor handles the image layer; Decal renders ON TOP in three.js compositing order. Keep as-is; just update position for the new mesh radius.

